meta {
  name: Webhook Lead Callback (Meta)
  type: http
  seq: 7
}

post {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/meta/webhook/{{integrationId}}
  body: json
  auth: none
}

headers {
  Content-Type: application/json
}

body:json {
  {
    "object": "page",
    "entry": [
      {
        "id": "123456789",
        "time": 1719100000,
        "changes": [
          {
            "field": "leadgen",
            "value": {
              "leadgen_id": "989906403816053",
              "page_id": "123456789",
              "form_id": "2217695302333588",
              "created_time": 1719100000
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}

docs {
  Simulates a Meta Lead Ads webhook callback.
  In production Meta signs the body with X-Hub-Signature-256.
  In development mode (NODE_ENV=development) HMAC is skipped.

  {{integrationId}} identifies the TENANT's Meta integration
  (ext.meta_tenant_config) — one Meta App/webhook subscription per tenant,
  shared across all of that tenant's orgs/branches. The org that a given
  lead belongs to is no longer implied by the URL; it's resolved from the
  page_id/form_id in this payload via ext.meta_page_form_org_map. A
  matching row must exist (see Create-Page-Org-Map.bru) or the lead is
  logged as "unmapped" and skipped — it will NOT land in any org's queue.

  A tenant-less variant also exists: POST {{baseUrl}}/meta/webhook (no
  integrationId segment) for a single Meta App shared across MULTIPLE
  tenants (see Webhook-Post-Shared.bru). That path resolves against the
  ext.meta_tenant_config row where tenant_id IS NULL, and resolves BOTH
  tenant_id and org_id from ext.meta_page_form_org_map (page_id/form_id
  are globally unique, not just unique per tenant).

  This body only carries leadgen_id/page_id/form_id metadata — that's
  all the real Meta webhook ever sends. The full field_data (including
  any address/job-title/demographic answers) is fetched server-side
  from the Graph API using the integration's access_token, so this
  request requires a real, working access_token + a real leadgen_id to
  exercise the full pipeline end-to-end. There is no local stub for the
  Graph API call.

  The service will:
  1. Verify HMAC signature (skipped in dev)
  2. Fetch lead details from Meta Graph API (field_data + reliable form_id live here)
  3. Resolve org_id + platform via ext.meta_page_form_org_map (form_id is
     authoritative; page_id is used only as a fallback default) — skips
     the lead if unmapped
  4. Resolve field keys using the tenant's field_mappings (falls back to
     DEFAULT_FIELD_MAPPINGS in meta.config.ts when unset)
  5. Insert into lms.marketing_leads (source = 'facebook' or 'instagram'
     based on the resolved platform) and ext.meta_leads
  6. Insert any address/job/demographic answers into ext.meta_lead_addresses,
     ext.meta_lead_professional, ext.meta_lead_demographics (only the
     tables with at least one matched field get a row)
  7. Insert any remaining unmapped form fields into ext.meta_lead_custom_fields
  8. Fire a crm_events pg_notify if not a duplicate

  Response: { received: true, processed: N, results: [...] } — each result's
  status is one of 'synced' | 'duplicate' | 'unmapped' | 'error'.

  To inspect the extracted data after running this, query
  ext.view_meta_leads_complete WHERE meta_lead_id = <leadgen_id>.
}
